Sure, here is an example of a JavaScript function that extracts a three-character code using regex:

```javascript
function extractCode(filename) {
    var regex = /(\w{3})(\.usfm)$/;
    var matches = filename.match(regex);
    return matches[1];
}

var filename = "57-1Jn.usfm";
console.log(extractCode(filename));  // Output: 1Jn
```

This function will look for a pattern of exactly three word characters (\w{3}), followed by the ".usfm" extension. The parentheses around the regex pattern capture the three character code, which is then returned by the function.

Note that \w represents any word character (equivalent to [a-zA-Z0-9_]). If you want to ensure that only alphabetic characters (no numbers or underscores) are considered valid for the code, you should use a letter range instead: /([a-zA-Z]{3})(\.usfm)$/.
